purpose: The commit fixes a bug related to queuing commands when HCI_UNREGISTER is set, preventing potential UAF (use-after-free) issues.
The commit removes an unnecessary include statement from n_hdlc.c, simplifying the code and reducing potential confusion in termios.h management.
The commit updates documentation for a new store metric 'N/A', which is added for store operations, to reflect changes in the report table.

The commit addresses two key issues related to vma lock handling during split vma and range unmapping, updating the hugetlb open vm_ops to allocate a new vma lock for the new vma and modifying the sharing code to ensure vma lock is indeed a condition for pmd sharing.
The commit adds documentation for two supplies, AVDD and MICVDD, in the rt5682s codec binding.
The commit fixes a resource leak in the zorro7xx_remove_one() function by adding an iounmap() call, which is a clear description of what the commit does and its technical changes.
The commit removes an unused work field from a struct, which is a straightforward refactoring change.
The commit modifies a struct member to make it signed, which is done to avoid warnings from static checkers when the key is NULL.
The commit sorts CONFIG_SURFACE_PLATFORMS, which is a configuration option for RISC-V defconfigs. It does not introduce any new functionality or fix existing bugs.

The commit introduces a new function mcp251xfd_is_fd_mode() to check if the chip's FIFOs are configured for CAN-FD mode, replacing an open-coded check. This change is related to CAN bus and its configuration.
The commit modifies selftests to skip rtc tests when RTC is not present, indicating a clear understanding of the technical changes.
The commit removes a redundant assignment to variable bytes, which is being re-assigned inside a following if block. This change cleans up a clang scan build warning related to dead code.
The commit modifies the kernel configuration to allow rcuscale without RCU Tasks, decoupling their presence.
The commit appears to be a refactoring change, removing duplicated text in spte.h file. The purpose is to improve code quality by reducing redundancy.

The commit reverts a change to prevent underflow in the dcn315 clk table, which was populated based on dcfclk states. This is done due to a no read situation caused by pmfw filling out the table when dcfclk states are disabled.

The commit adds a compatible string for the Renesas RZ/V2L SoC's Bifrost Mali-G31 GPU, which is a specific hardware component. The changes are related to device tree bindings and do not appear to introduce any new functionality or fix existing bugs.
The commit renames a struct to make it more consistent with other names in the driver, which is a clear and specific technical change.

The commit fixes a clang -Wformat warning in the net: amd-xgbe driver by changing the format specifier from %hx to %x, which is more accurate given that the argument will be promoted to an int. This change aligns with C11 standards and recommendations in Documentation/core-api/printk-formats.rst.
The commit appears to fix a compatibility issue related to branch range checks in MIPS architecture, specifically addressing a warning triggered by signed compare operations.
The commit removes an unwanted case from a function, simplifying its logic and reducing dependencies on the hal layer.
The commit declares non-global symbols as static to fix sparse warnings introduced while adding errata, indicating a clear understanding of the technical changes.
The commit is related to display bindings, specifically addressing an issue with MDSS nodes where interrupt flags are incorrectly specified on consumers.

The commit appears to be a refactoring change, allocating space for arrays in struct ctrl_ref, which is likely an improvement to the code's maintainability and performance. The commit message provides clear context about its purpose.
The commit adds support for new SoCs and PMICs to the socinfo driver, which is a clear indication of its purpose.

The commit appears to be a bug-fixing commit that improves the recognition of chip cuts in the rtl8xxxu wifi driver, allowing it to correctly identify all possible chip versions instead of printing 'unknown' when the version is greater than E.
The commit is clearly about removing a custom software enable count from PRCMU clocks, which is a technical change that can be understood by analyzing the code context.
The commit aims to remove #ifdef CONFIG_XIP_KERNEL usage by grouping related code together, improving code organization and reducing conditional compilation.
The commit enables QUP and GPI DMA hardware, which is necessary for adding functioning I2C nodes later.
The commit is clearly a refactoring effort to improve code quality, specifically fixing comments and adhering to coding style guidelines.
The commit fixes an infinite loop issue that occurs when failing to acquire a HW semaphore, which is necessary for resource release.
The commit updates the pcm3168a driver to use modern ASoC DAI format terminology, replacing old style defines for bus clocks.
The commit removes an IS_SWAPFILE hack, which is deemed pointless as IS_SWAPFILE is always defined.
The commit implements a GTP echo response, addressing a situation where there is no userspace daemon to handle GTP messages.

The commit replaces cpumask_next_* functions with cpumask_first_* where appropriate, adds a new function cpumask_first_zero(), and makes some minor adjustments. The changes aim to improve the functionality of the cpumask system.

The commit removes a call to 'dtim_assoc' IOVAR, which is no longer supported in the firmware, causing a failure when trying to get TIM information from firmware. This change ensures that the host driver will no longer try to get TIM information from firmware.
The commit adds support for a platform without amplifier by adding a board config adl_rt5682 to support alc5682 headset codec, following Intel BT offload design.

The commit is related to io_uring/net, specifically addressing an issue with zerocopy sendmsg when unsupported by socket. It appears to be a fix for a specific scenario where the previous patch failed to handle protocols that don't support zerocopy send requests.
The commit modifies the kernel documentation to conditionally load xeCJK depending on the existence of the 'Noto Sans CJK SC' font, preventing potential errors when compiling LaTeX documents.
The commit modifies the checkpatch script to allow 'case' macros, which are already used in some kernel drivers.
The commit is clearly about replacing simple-KMS helpers with atomic helpers, which will allow for easier code sharing among drivers.
The commit adds a jpeg decode worker interface to enable parallel processing on MT8195, improving performance.
The commit removes pointless VPRINTK() calls and ata_scsi_dump_cdb(), improving code quality by reducing unnecessary logging and information duplication.
The commit adds support for zstate during extended vblank, which is a specific technical change that improves the system's behavior.

The commit updates a function pointer prototype to match reality, fixing a CFI violation caused by an incorrect type of reset_type parameter in hqd_destroy() callback. The change is made to prevent a failure when booting a kernel compiled with CONFIG_CFI_CLANG on a machine with an RX 6700 XT.

The commit corrects a property name error in the dt-bindings for pinctrl, specifically changing 'reset' to 'resets', and adds missing 'additionalProperties'. This is a clear description of what the commit does and its technical changes.

The commit is addressing a warning generated by GCC 12 regarding an array subscript out of bounds in ath9k_mac.c, specifically in the ath9k_hw_resettxqueue function. The fix involves silencing this warning by setting its severity to W=1+.
The commit changes the way power management is handled for the sun8i-ss crypto module, using pm_runtime_resume_and_get instead of pm_runtime_get_sync. This change aims to simplify code.
The commit splits out fixed file installation and removal from io_uring, moving it to the filetable code where it belongs. It also updates the helpers to take a ctx rather than an io_kiocb.

The commit updates the device tree bindings for the nxp, imx8mq-vpu media driver to support separate nodes for G1 and G2 decoder blocks. This is done by updating the power-domain controller's driver and adding support for independent fusion of these blocks.
The commit appears to be a refactoring change, removing an unused macro and combining its contents into another macro.
